# Query to get total winning percentage for each team from the Teams table, grouping by year and teamID
query = "SELECT Teams.yearID, Teams.teamID, Teams.lgID, Teams.franchID, Teams.W as totalWins, Teams.G as totalGames, CAST(Teams.W AS FLOAT) / CAST(Teams.G AS FLOAT) * 100 as winPercentage FROM Teams GROUP BY Teams.yearID, Teams.teamID ORDER BY Teams.yearID, Teams.teamID"
lahman2014_teams = pd.read_sql(query, lahman2014_conn)

Description¶

For the table above, I queried the sum of total wins (W) and total games (G) for each team for each year they played and then calculated their win percentage using the formula (number of wins / number of games * 100). This table includes a lot of extra teams that are NOT in the salaries table and will be ignored when joining the tables. This table also starts at the year 1871 while the salaries table starts at 1985. There are NO missing values in this table.

In [ ]:
# Query to get salaries for each team by year by using sum and grouping by year and teamID again
query = "SELECT Salaries.yearID, Salaries.teamID, Salaries.lgID, sum(Salaries.salary) as totalPayroll FROM Salaries GROUP BY Salaries.yearID, Salaries.teamID ORDER BY Salaries.yearID, Salaries.teamID"
lahman2014_payrolls = pd.read_sql(query, lahman2014_conn)

# Pandas right join into salaries (the smaller table) the values that match yearID and teamID from the teams table
lahman2014_payrollwithwins = pd.merge(lahman2014_teams, lahman2014_payrolls,  how='inner', left_on=['teamID','lgID', 'yearID'], right_on = ['teamID','lgID', 'yearID'])

Description¶

For the table above, I INNER joined the two previously created tables (salaries and win percentages over time) to show how payroll has affected win percentage and plot any relations in the coming parts. While the two tables separately DID NOT have missing data, there are many values that would not match up if I did a left/right join, leading to missing values because of the timeline difference between the tables. Using an inner join ensured that only exact matching records of ALL THREE teamID, lgID, and year were joined together, leading to no missing values. This was checked with pd.isnull.values.any() which returned false.

Question 1¶

The most clear trend in the distribution of payrolls conditioned on time is the increase of payroll over time. Take the New York Mets (Dark Blue, highest line) for example, they started at around $0.25x10^8 total payroll in 1990 and their total team payroll is 8 TIMES that in 2014. Another trend that is seen is the spread between different teams in payrolls. While there is a heavy positive correlation between time and increased payroll, not all teams have increased at the same rate. The spread was much tighter in 1990 than it is in 2014, with some teams still making around the same that they made in 1990.

Question 2¶

While the mean payrols have been rising a lot through the time periods, the mean win percentage has largely remained the same, with a limit of around 60% for most teams. I believe that there is a slight correlation between higher payrolls and win percentages, as can be seen most clearly in the 2006-2010 time period. But it is a very weak correlation since every time period, the mean win percentage does not keep increasing as mean payroll is increasing and there is a lot of variance in the plot.

Once again, the New York Yankees stand out nearly every year as having a high pay mean and high win percentage mean, showing that they are paying good money for good players.

The Oakland A's spending is marked by an "X" in each time period. While their mean pay has nearly doubled since 1990-1995 (going from about .35x10^8 to .65x10^8), their win percentage has remained around 50-60% and is usually an outlier in the lower paid teams for having a high win percentage, so the Moneyball year is, in fact, a thing.

3.1 Standardizing across years¶

Problem 5¶

In [ ]:
filtered_payrollswithwins = lahman2014_payrollwithwins[lahman2014_payrollwithwins['yearID'] >= 1990].reset_index()
standardized_payrollwithwins = pd.DataFrame(filtered_payrollswithwins)
standardized_values = []

# Get mean and standard deviation of each year (j)
payroll_mean = standardized_payrollwithwins.groupby('yearID')['totalPayroll'].mean()
payroll_std = standardized_payrollwithwins.groupby('yearID')['totalPayroll'].std()

for name, group in standardized_payrollwithwins.groupby('teamID'):
    year_group = group.groupby('yearID')['totalPayroll']
    for key, payroll in year_group:
        team_payroll_in_year = payroll.iloc[0]
        standardized_values.append((team_payroll_in_year - payroll_mean[key]) / payroll_std[key])
    
standardized_payrollwithwins['standarizedPayroll'] = standardized_values
standardized_payrollwithwins

Question 3¶

Standardizing the payrolls meant that for each year, the differences between teams is made more pronounced by subtracting the mean payroll and dividing by the standard deviation. This results in a smaller spead on the X axis, centering it around 0, clearly showing who spent more than average in that year and who spent less. The plots are also all similar since the payroll has been standardized instead of it being previously vastly different numbers on the X axis. Once again, a small positive correlation between payroll and win percentage can be seen, but for the most part, the data is very spread out with high variance, and does not lead to any solid conclusions on payroll having a large effect on wins.

Question 4¶

The plot above shows a few key team's efficiency throughout the Moneyball period. This plot shows more than just increased win percentage as a function increased payroll as was shown for Questions 2 and 3. This plot shows how efficient a team is at reaching their expected win rate based on their pay. The more efficient they are, the more easily they can live up to their "expected pay worth." For example, a team that has a very high pay roll but a very low win percentage would be considered low efficiency and vice-versa.

The Oakland's efficiency during the Moneyball year (2002) is extremely high, almost matching the efficiency of the New York Yankees, yet at a lower budget. This shows that teams with lower payrolls can be as efficient as teams with higher payrolls, but there are still teams with lower payrolls that severely underperform, such as Tampa Bay, which can be seen in the first plot to be among the lowest. Although Tampa Bay is not as efficient as the other teams, their efficiency has increased over time despite not having a large change in payroll. In conclusion, payroll does have an effect on a teams win rate BUT it does not always result in an increased win rate if not spent efficiently like Oakland does.

1. Data Collection of Salaries¶

For collecting the data, I will be using html requests and urlparse to import data from two websites that have the latest data on Team payroll and Standings:

  1. https://www.spotrac.com/mlb/payroll/ which will be used to get payroll data for each team and player from 2015-2020 to fill the sqlite database. This will be the Salaries table. The one issue with this source is that it requires a premium subscription to access the data before 2019, so I will only be using it as a proof of concept.
  2. https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/majors/2020-standings.shtml which will be used to get team win data by year. This will be the Teams table.
In [ ]:
import requests
from urllib.parse import urlparse

salaries_page_2020 = requests.get('https://www.spotrac.com/mlb/payroll/2020/') #Extracting Salaries from 2020 only HTML via URL
salaries_page_2020_text = salaries_page_2020.content #Getting the content of the page

pd_tables = pd.read_html(salaries_page_2020_text, flavor = 'bs4') #Read the table from the html
salaries_table_2020 = pd_tables[0] #Store the table

# Getting Team names to gather each team's specific roster payroll later
all_team_names = salaries_table_2020['Team'].tolist()

# Removing clutter text
all_team_names.remove("League Average")
all_team_names.remove("League Average")

# Loop through teams, lowercase them, remove team moniker, and add dashes so that URL parsing works
for i in range(len(all_team_names)):
    all_team_names[i] = all_team_names[i][:len(all_team_names[i]) - 4].lower().strip().replace(" ", "-")
    
# Now that we have all team names formatted, we can begin extracting individual teams roster data for 2020, 2019, and 2018
team_payrolls_2019_2020 = pd.DataFrame()
for year in range(2019,2021,1):
    for team_name in all_team_names:
        request = requests.get("https://www.spotrac.com/mlb/{}/payroll/{}/".format(team_name, year))
        request_tables = pd.read_html(request.content, flavor = 'bs4') #Read the table from the html
        payroll_table = request_tables[0] #Store the table
        payroll_table.insert(0, 'Year', year) # Insert year
        payroll_table.insert(1, 'Team_Name', team_name) # Insert year
        payroll_table = payroll_table.drop(columns=['Signing Bonus', 'Incentives', 'Lux. Tax Salary', 'Status']) # Drop columns that are not needed
        payroll_table.columns = ['Year', 'Team_Name', 'Player_Name', 'Age', 'Position', 'Base_Salary', 'Payroll_Salary', 'Adjusted_Salary', "Payroll_Perc"] # Give better column names without spaces for SQLite database
        team_payrolls_2019_2020 = team_payrolls_2019_2020.append(payroll_table) # Add the table to the collective
        
team_payrolls_2019_2020 # The completed salaries table with years

2. Analysis of Salaries table¶

The Salaries table includes all teams and players from 2019-2020 salaries split into base,payroll, and adjusted and also includes age and player position, allowing for better analysis of team payrolls and MLB stats. This will allow the database to answer more questions such as "do higher payed players tend to be older"" or "Which positions pay best on average?" That is why I decided to keep that data intact. I only removed three columns, which were Signing Bonus, Incentives, Lux. Tax Salary, and Status. I do not believe the signing bonus and incentives for a player to join are useful in determining trends of the team. I also ignored inactive and injured players salaries as the purpose of the database is to show trends among active teams win rates as related to pay.

If I can access the tables for 2015,2016,2017, and 2018, I can very easily add them into the table because I used variables to access each page and its data, nothing is hard coded and the code is easily adjustable to include even future years if needed. To gain access to older data, I would need some form of authentication to go with my HTML request, most likely my login token which can be sent with each request, but I do not have $30 for premium data access. But I believe that this is a great proof of concept.

Now that the Salaries table has been accessed, cleaned, and stored into one single Pandas table, it can be exported to a SQLite table.

# Creating the database
mlb_teams_and_salaries_2020 = sql.connect("mlb_teams_and_salaries_2020.db")

# Using Pandas export function to_sql
team_payrolls_2019_2020.to_sql('Salaries', con=mlb_teams_and_salaries_2020)

#Insuring data got stored properly
query = "SELECT * FROM Salaries"
mlb_teams_salaries = pd.read_sql(query, mlb_teams_and_salaries_2020)
